                arabicText: "التاسع : عن عُمَرَ رضي الله عنه ، عَنِ النَّبيِّ صلى الله عليه وسلم ، قَالَ : (( لاَ يُسْأَلُ الرَّجُلُ فِيمَ ضَرَبَ امْرَأَتَهُ )) رواه أبو داود وغيره",
                englishText: "The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) said: \"A man will not be questioned as to why he beat his wife.\" (Abū Dāwūd)",
                grade: "Hasan",
                collection: "Abu Dawud",
                commentary: `This ḥadīth needs to be understood in its proper context. Allāh has granted the husband the responsibility of seeing to the moral and spiritual growth of his wife and family. He has to ensure that they practise upon the laws of the sharī'ah by utilizing various means of teaching and encouragement and he may reprimand them within the boundaries of Islāmic law if they choose to pursue the wrong path. The ḥadīth means that a husband will ordinarily not be questioned why he reprimanded his spouse because it could have been because of a personal and confidential marital issue that may compromise the integrity of his marriage or spouse. In such cases, a husband will be permitted to reprimand her within the confines of sharī'ah. The husband's response will be confined to the marriage and should be governed by his fear of Allāh. A husband should not use this ḥadīth as a license to abuse his wife. The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) himself nurtured, taught and admonished his spouses in such a beautiful manner that not only his spouses, but the entire Ummah benefitted tremendously from his style and approach. The ḥadīth is relevant to the chapter because, even though a husband will not be questioned for reprimanding his wife, he should remember that Allāh is watching him at all times; hence, he should not abuse his authority.`
