                englishText: "The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) prohibited the throwing of pebbles using the index finger and thumb and said: \"It neither kills game nor causes any destruction to the enemy, however, it bursts an eye and breaks a tooth.\" (Bukhārī, Muslim) According to another narration, a relative of ('Abdullāh) ibn Mughaffal (رضي الله عنه) threw pebbles using his index finger and thumb. His relative stopped him from doing so and said: \"The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) prohibited throwing pebbles using the index finger and thumb and said: 'It does not kill game.'\" However, the person did it again. He then said: \"I told you that the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) prohibited this, yet you continue doing so. I will not speak to you again.\"",
                grade: "Sahih",
                collection: "Al-Bukhari & Muslim",
                commentary: `Imām Nawawī stated that this ḥadīth proves the permissibility of remaining aloof from one who is involved in innovation and sin. It is prohibited to remain aloof from someone for more than three days due to personal or worldly reasons. However, if there is a valid Islāmic reason such as sin or transgression, then one is permitted to do so for more than three days. An example of this was the case of those Ṣaḥābah of Madīnah Munawwarah who severed ties with three other Ṣaḥābah for approximately fifty days because the latter remained absent from the Battle of Tabūk without any valid reason. The Ṣaḥābah of the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) held every prophetic command in high regard and could not bear others breaking it because they were fully convinced that the Sunnah is an embodiment of blessing and goodness.`
