                englishText: "News reached the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) that the tribe of 'Amr ibn 'Auf were involved in a dispute. So, the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) left with some of his Ṣaḥābah in order to reconcile between them. The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) was delayed and it was the time of ṣalāh, so Bilāl came to Abū Bakr (رضي الله عنه) and said: \"O Abū Bakr! The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) has been delayed and it is the time of ṣalāh. Will you lead the people in ṣalāh?\" He replied: \"Yes, if you like.\" Bilāl gave the iqāmah and Abū Bakr stepped forward and said the takbīr (Allāhu Akbar) with the people doing the same behind him. The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) then arrived, walked through the rows and stood in the first row. The people began clapping (to draw the attention of Abū Bakr). Abū Bakr (رضي الله عنه) was not in the habit of looking about in his ṣalāh, but when the people clapped repeatedly, Abū Bakr turned around and saw the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ). The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) indicated to him (to remain in his place). Abū Bakr raised his hand, praised Allāh and walked backwards until he stood in the row. The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) then stepped forward and led the people in ṣalāh. When he had completed, he turned to the people and said: \"Why did you start clapping when you experienced something in ṣalāh? Clapping is for women. When anything happens to you in ṣalāh, you should say subḥānallāh (glory be to Allāh), because when you hear someone saying subḥānallāh, you will turn around. O Abū Bakr, what stopped you from leading the people in ṣalāh when I had directed you to do so?\" Abū Bakr (رضي الله عنه) replied: \"It is not proper for the son of Abū Quḥāfah to lead the people in ṣalāh in the presence of the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ).\" (Bukhārī, Muslim)",
