                englishText: "He heard the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) delivering a sermon in which he spoke about the camel (in the time of Ṣāliḥ) and the person who hamstrung it. The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) said: \"When the most wretched of them rushed forward,\" means that a powerful leader, who was vicious and fierce, rushed forward to hamstring the camel. The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) then spoke about women and advised regarding them by saying: \"You go and strike your wife as you would a slave and then perhaps engage in intercourse with her at the end of the day!\" He then admonished them about laughing at a person who breaks wind by saying: \"Why do you laugh at something which you yourself do.\" (Bukhārī, Muslim)",
                grade: "Sahih",
                collection: "Al-Bukhari & Muslim",
                commentary: `This ḥadīth highlights three aspects. Firstly, the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) informed the Ṣaḥābah about the incident of Ṣāliḥ and the camel that was miraculously granted to him. Secondly, he advised against unjustly beating women. Thirdly, he advised the Ṣaḥābah not to laugh at someone who passes wind because it is natural and normal to do so.`
