                commentary: `Usāmah (رضي الله عنه) assumed that the man was a disbeliever and that his declaration of the kalimah was worthless. He thought that it was uttered without sincere belief and only to avoid being killed. He was under the impression that a person's blood becomes sacred only when he accepts Islām by heart, not by outward expression. Due to his mistake in judgement, Usāmah (رضي الله عنه) was not sinful for killing him and there was no retribution. However, the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) emphasised the correct ruling for the Ummah to follow, which is to judge people according to their apparent words and deeds. We have no access to their hearts; hence, it is not permissible for us to act according to our assumptions or suspicions.`
