                commentary: `This ḥadīth explains that the noble Ṣaḥābī, 'Abd al-Raḥmān ibn 'Auf (رضي الله عنه), was of the opinion that the treasures of the world which were given to them was the reward for their good deeds and that they would therefore not receive any reward in the Hereafter. This showed his concern for success in the Hereafter. It is advisable to mention the bounties of Allāh (ﷻ) that one enjoys, so that one may be grateful for them and express ones inability to appreciate them fully. Humility is a virtue. Despite 'Abd al-Raḥmān ibn 'Auf (رضي الله عنه) being one of the 'Asharah Mubassharah (the ten Ṣaḥābah who were promised Paradise), he regarded Muṣ'ab ibn 'Umayr (رضي الله عنه) to be more virtuous than himself.`
