                englishText: "A woman brought a woven shawl to the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) and said: 'I wove it with my own hands so that you could wear it.' The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) accepted it from her as he was in need of it. Later on, he came to us wearing it as a loincloth and someone said: 'This shawl is so beautiful. Give it to me to wear.' He (ﷺ) said: 'Yes.' The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) then sat down in the assembly. After some time he returned home, folded it and sent it to him. The people said to him: 'Your action was not appropriate. The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) wore it out of need and you asked him for it knowing that he never refuses a request!' The man replied: 'By Allāh, I did not ask him for it in order to wear it. I asked him for it so that it could be my burial shroud.' Sahl (رضي الله عنه) said: \"And it was indeed his burial shroud.\" (Bukhārī)",
                grade: "Sahih",
                collection: "Al-Bukhari",
                commentary: `This ḥadīth illustrates the generosity and noble character of the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ). It is permissible to derive benefit from the relics of the pious. Exchanging gifts creates mutual love and unity. One should not refuse a gift without a valid reason. It is meritorious to continuously ponder over death.`
