                englishText: "The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) said: \"None of you should desire death because if he is righteous, it is possible that he will increase (in good deeds) and if he is a sinner, it is possible that he will repent.\" (Bukhārī, Muslim) A narration of Muslim from Abū Hurayrah (رضي الله عنه) states that the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) said: \"None of you should desire death nor supplicate for it before it comes to him because when a person passes away, his deeds come to an end and the extended life of a believer accrues good deeds in his favour.\"",
                grade: "Sahih",
                collection: "Al-Bukhari & Muslim",
                commentary: `From this ḥadīth, we learn that it is not permissible for a person to desire death due to financial difficulties, ill-health or personal problems because this is a sign of displeasure with the decree of Allāh (ﷻ). One should instead be content with the decree of Allāh (ﷻ) and exercise patience. One should also not desire death because this closes the doors of repentance. A Muslim should value and appreciate every moment of life so that he may engage in some form of good.`
