                commentary: `The ḥadīth defines righteousness and sin. It teaches us that the best form of righteousness is to be embodied with admirable character. This encompasses, amongst other things, to deal with people with a pleasant countenance, to save others from harm, to be kind and helpful, to love for others what one loves for oneself, to be just and to give preference to others over oneself. Sin is defined as having two attributes. It creates doubts and uneasiness within a person that he is committing a sin, and it leads to a fear that one will be embarrassed if others get to know about it.`
