                collection: "Abu Dawud",
                commentary: `This ḥadīth teaches us that when one sits in any place, one should remember Allāh for a short while. One should at least recite the du'ā' which is mentioned in ḥadīth 832, 833 and 834. A person should endeavour to remember Allāh in all conditions. Allāh says, "They who remember Allāh while standing, sitting and lying down, and they think about the creation of the heavens and earth. 'Our Sustainer, You have not created all this without a purpose. We glorify Your purity so save us from the punishment of the Fire.'" (Sūrah Āl 'Imrān, 191) The virtue of remembering Allāh at the time of sleeping can be gauged from a narration of Abū Muray'ah al-'Ajalī in Fatḥ al-Bārī, which states that the bed of a person who retires to it in a state of wuḍū' and falls off to sleep while engaged in Allāh's remembrance, becomes a masjid and he is regarded as one engaged in ṣalāh therein until he awakens.`
