                englishText: "Rarely would the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) rise from a gathering without making the following supplication: 'O Allāh, grant us such fear of You that will be a barrier between us and Your disobedience, and such obedience of You that will convey us to Your Paradise, and such conviction that will make all the calamities of this world easy for us. O Allāh! Enable us to benefit from our hearing, eyesight and strength for as long as You keep us alive and make these survive our death. Grant us revenge from those who oppress us and assist us against those who oppose us. Do not make us experience disaster in our religion. Do not make the world our main concern nor the limit of our knowledge. Do not grant authority over us to those who have no mercy for us.'\" (Tirmidhī)",
                grade: "Hasan",
                collection: "Tirmidhi",
                commentary: `This is a beautiful and comprehensive du'ā' which the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) would make at the conclusion of a gathering. In it one seeks the goodness of both worlds. Fear of Allāh should be to the extent that it saves one from His disobedience. The stronger a person's belief and conviction is in Allāh and the Hereafter, the more insignificant the difficulties of this life will seem. Our senses are a trust from Allāh and we should benefit from them by utilising them in the correct avenues. One should hand over all matters pertaining to his enemies and oppressors to Allāh. The worst trial that a person can experience is with regard to his religion by committing sin and not doing good actions.`
