                narrator: "Abū Hurayrah (رضي الله عنه)",
                arabicText: "وعنه ، قَالَ : قَالَ رسول الله صلى الله عليه وسلم : (( مَنْ رَآنِي في المَنَامِ فَسَيَرَانِي فِي اليَقَظَةِ – أَوْ كَأَنَّما رَآنِي فِي اليَقَظَةِ – لاَ يَتَمَثَّلُ الشَّيْطَانُ بِي )) متفقٌ عَلَيْهِ .",
                englishText: "The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) said: \"One who sees me when he is asleep will see me while awake – or it is as if he had seen me while awake – Shaiṭān cannot take my form.\" (Bukhārī, Muslim)",
                grade: "Sahih",
                collection: "Bukhari & Muslim",
                commentary: `Some scholars say that one who saw the Messenger (ﷺ) in his sleep will be blessed with meeting the Messenger (ﷺ) in the Hereafter. Ibn Baṭṭāl said that one who sees the Messenger (ﷺ) in his sleep will receive confirmation of the validity of this vision while he is awake; it does not refer to the Hereafter because all Muslims will see him in the Hereafter, irrespective of whether they had seen him in a dream or not. Ibn Ḥajar stated, "One who sees the Messenger (ﷺ) in a dream, will be honoured by a special meeting with the Messenger (ﷺ) after his demise. Beholding the Messenger (ﷺ) is a sign that he (ﷺ) will intercede on one's behalf." The Messenger (ﷺ) is the leader of guidance, whilst Shaiṭān is the leader of evil and misguidance. These are two opposing forces, hence Shaiṭān cannot adopt the form of the Messenger (ﷺ). Just as the Messenger (ﷺ) was divinely protected from Shaiṭān's influence during his lifetime, he (ﷺ) has also been safeguarded against his mischief after his demise.`
