                commentary: `This ḥadīth points to the virtue of 'Ā'ishah (رضي الله عنها). From amongst all the noble wives, Jibra'īl (عليه السلام) only conveyed salām to Khadījah (رضي الله عنها) and 'Ā'ishah (رضي الله عنها). It is compulsory to reply to the salām of a third person. When replying to the salām of a third person via an intermediary, one should should say 'alaihi' instead of 'alaikum'. When reading a letter, email, etc. it is compulsory to verbally reply to a salām. It is more virtuous to reply with additional words as 'Ā'ishah (رضي الله عنها) had done. It is permissible for a strange man to send salām to a pious woman via her maḥram if no fear of evil exists between them. In this ḥadīth, 'Ā'ishāh (رضي الله عنها) only replied to the salām of Jiba'īl (عليه السلام), however one may also offer salām to the person who conveys it.`
