                arabicText: "وعن أنس رضي الله عنه ، قَالَ : قَالَ رسول الله صلى الله عليه وسلم : (( إِذَا سَلَّمَ عَلَيْكُمْ أَهْلُ الكِتَابِ فَقُولُوا : وَعَلَيْكُمْ )) متفقٌ عَلَيْهِ .",
                englishText: "The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) said: \"If the people of the Book offer the salām to you, reply by saying: 'And upon you.'\" (Bukhārī, Muslim)",
                grade: "Sahih",
                collection: "Bukhari & Muslim",
                commentary: `According to a narration of Bukhārī, "Whenever the Jews used to greet the Messenger (ﷺ), they would say, 'Assāmu 'alaykum' which means, 'Death be upon you.'" The Messenger (ﷺ) used to merely answer them with the words "And upon you." 'Ā'ishah said, "Death be upon you, and may Allāh curse you and may His anger be upon you." She asked, "Did you not hear what they said?" The Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) replied, "Did you not hear what I said? I replied to them. My supplication against them will be accepted, whilst their supplication regarding me will not be accepted." This ḥadīth teaches us that one should reply to the greeting of a non-Muslim with the words, "وعليكم" or merely "عليكم" instead of "وعليكم السلام." Some scholars have suggested that it is better to reply to a non-Muslim with the words 'هداك الله' meaning "May Allāh guide you!"`
