                arabicText: "وعن أنس رضي الله عنه ، قَالَ : أَقْبَلْنَا مَعَ النَّبِيِّ صلى الله عليه وسلم حَتَّى إِذَا كُنَّا بِظَهْرِ المَدِينَةِ ، قَالَ : (( آيِبُونَ ، تَائِبُونَ ، عَابِدُونَ ، لِرَبِّنَا حَامِدُونَ )) فَلَمْ يَزَلْ يَقُولُ ذَلِكَ حَتَّى قَدِمْنَا المَدِينَةَ . رواه مسلم .",
                englishText: "We returned with the Messenger of Allāh (ﷺ) until we were in sight of Madīnah. He said: 'We are returning, repenting, worshipping, and praising Him.' He continued saying this until we reached Madīnah.\" (Muslim, Tirmidhī, Aḥmad)",
                grade: "Sahih",
                collection: "Muslim",
                commentary: `When returning from a journey, one should continuously recite this du'ā' from the outskirts of one's home town. The du'ā' teaches us not to be proud of our accomplishments on the journey. Instead, we should realise that we are merely Allāh's (ﷻ) servants and every success is only through His grace and kindness. We should therefore praise Him and request forgiveness for our shortcomings. The sequence of the du'ā' is significant. One first repents as a form of purification, then one turns towards good actions and finally praises Allāh (ﷻ) for granting him the ability.`
