                collection: "Muslim",
                commentary: `This ḥadīth confirms the verse of the Qur'ān: \"Whoever brings a good action, receives ten times as much.\" (Sūrah al-An'ām, 160). Allāh showers His special mercies upon a person who recites ṣalawāt, and He mentions him to the high-ranking angels. Being mentioned and remembered by Allāh is the greatest of bounties as there can be no greater honour than this. This ḥadīth mentions a reward of ten, while another ḥadīth mentions seventy. Scholars have given three answers to this apparent contradiction: 1. Allāh first rewarded the Ummah by ten and then increased it to seventy due to His kindness. 2. The exact reward depends on the occasion and the sincerity of the person who recites it. 3. The reward of seventy applies to the day of Jumu'ah because some narrations state that actions done on Jumu'ah are multiplied seventy times.`
